-- SHADOW-SEMANTICS cell D21 (matrix row 29): the S5 CARVE-OUT at MULTI-TYPARAM
-- width.  `useIface : Ix a i => a -> i -> Int` calls `get` on its own dict-bound
-- `=>` constraint variable, inside a module that shadows `get`.  S5's carve-out says
-- such a receiver DISPATCHES -- writing `Ix a i =>` is an explicit, written-down
-- request to resolve through the interface.  It does.
-- Expected: check accepts; run/build print 4 then 3.
--
--   println (useIface (Box 3) 1)  -- S5 carve-out: dispatches to impl Ix Box Int
--                                 -- `get (Box n) i = n + i` -> 3 + 1 = 4
--   println (get 3 1)             -- no `=>` in sight, grounded Int receiver:
--                                 -- S2, the standalone, `n * i` -> 3 * 1 = 3
--
-- 🚨 THE VALUE 4,3 IS NUMERICALLY IDENTICAL TO d11's OLD *BUG* OUTPUT.  It is not the
-- same thing, and it will look like a regression to someone.  d11's 4 came from an
-- UNQUALIFIED `get (Box 3) 1` that the impl universe STOLE -- the pre-inversion S2 this
-- whole arc abolished.  d21's 4 is dispatch the author EXPLICITLY REQUESTED by writing
-- `Ix a i =>`.  Same number, opposite verdict.  DO NOT "FIX" THIS BACK.
--
-- ✅ WAS A KNOWN-BAD GAP ROW; CLOSED 2026-07-17 BY #604 -- WITH NO CHANGE TO THE SHADOW
-- MACHINERY.  #54 added this fixture pinned REJECT/REJECT/REJECT and wrote that it must
-- be RE-PROBED, not assumed, the day #604 landed.  #604 landed; re-probed; it ACCEPTs,
-- and 4/400/3 at N-way width proves the per-receiver dict dispatch is real rather than a
-- monomorphisation accident.  The ledger row went RED on the next run -- the third time
-- that mechanism has caught a fix landing (d10/S-1, d11/S-3, now d21).
--
-- The cause was never here.  `Ty`'s `TyApp Ty Ty` (frontend/ast.mdk) is BINARY, so
-- `Ix a i` nests as `TyApp (TyApp (TyCon "Ix") a) i`; `extractConstraints` in
-- frontend/parser.mdk matched only the ONE-argument `TyApp (TyCon iface _) arg`, so no
-- arm matched and EVERY >=2-ARGUMENT CONSTRAINT WAS SILENTLY DISCARDED at parse
-- (`TyConstrained []`).  S5's antecedent ("a dict-bound `=>` constraint variable") was
-- false because there was no constraint at all.  `definerReceiverIsDictVar` handles
-- multi-argument constraints correctly -- it never received one.  #604 taught
-- `extractConstraints` to walk the whole spine and the carve-out started working on its
-- own.  ⚠️ An earlier version of this header blamed `definerReceiverIsDictVar`; that was
-- wrong, asserted from reading rather than probed, and it would have sent the next agent
-- to the wrong file.
--
-- Pre-#54 this file was SILENT WRONGNESS, strictly worse than d11's loud panic:
--   check  -> exit 0, reporting `useIface : a -> b -> Int` (constraint dropped)
--   run    -> E-PANIC `unknown op '*'`
--   build  -> exit 0, binary printed `69867028434928` then `3` -- a RAW HEAP POINTER
-- #54 traded that for a located reject; #604 turned the reject into the right answer.
--
-- NOTE: this fixture REQUIRES #604 (it is the only cell here whose behaviour depends on
-- a `=>` constraint surviving the parser).  Its importer twin i10 does not.
interface Ix a i where
  get : a -> i -> Int

data Box = Box Int

impl Ix Box Int where
  get (Box n) i = n + i

get : Int -> Int -> Int
get n i = n * i

useIface : Ix a i => a -> i -> Int
useIface x i = get x i

main =
  println (useIface (Box 3) 1)
  println (get 3 1)
